etymologies: late Middle English; earliest use found in Guy de Chauliac's Grande Chirurgie. From post-classical Latin respirativus respiratory from classical Latin respīrāt-, past participial stem of respīrāre + -īvus

notes.text: Now chiefly in English-language texts from non-English-speaking countries.

definitions: Of or relating to the processes of oxygen transport, gas exchange, and aerobic respiration.
